Compile a comprehensive, year‑by‑year dataset for the “15. ASSET UNDER DEVELOPMENT” line item that includes (1) opening and closing balances, additions, transfers to/from vessels and equipment, transfers from other non‑current assets, and capitalized interest costs; (2) all related service‑related revenues and expenses such as management and administrative services revenue, ship‑management fees (income), debt‑guarantee compensation, other income, charter‑hire expenses, share‑option expense recharge, interest income on short‑term loans, and interest expense on deposits payable, together with the total for each year; (3) detailed metadata on each contractual agreement or transaction (counterparty name, type of agreement, year recorded, cash consideration received where applicable, and any receivables/payables with subsidiaries). The data product should support calculations of year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes, identification of the years with the highest or lowest values for any line item, and analysis of how specific agreements (e.g., with Keppel, BP, Golar Management, Golar Power) correspond to changes in the financial figures.

Collect a unified, year‑by‑year dataset (covering at least 2017‑2019) for the company's defined‑benefit pension plans that includes:  

- Weighted‑average actuarial assumptions for each year (discount rate, expected rate of return on plan assets, rate of compensation increase).  
- Projected benefit obligation and accumulated benefit obligation values at the beginning and end of each year.  
- Detailed components of the projected benefit obligation: service cost, interest cost, actuarial losses (experience and assumptions), benefit payments, foreign‑currency exchange effects, and any acquisition‑related additions.  
- Plan‑asset side information: fair value of plan assets at the beginning and end of each year, actual gains/losses on assets, contributions, foreign‑currency effects, and the resulting unfunded status.  
- Liability‑maturity analysis: weighted‑average duration of the defined‑benefit obligation and non‑discounted benefit‑payment amounts broken into the maturity buckets (≤ 1 yr, > 1‑≤ 5 yr, > 5‑≤ 10 yr, > 10‑≤ 20 yr, > 20‑≤ 30 yr, > 30 yr).  

The dataset should enable users to calculate absolute and percentage changes between years, identify the year with the highest compensation‑increase rate, compare discount‑rate trends, and analyze how assumptions, obligation growth, asset performance, and liability duration interact over time.

Create a consolidated dataset for Advanced Energy Industries covering fiscal years 2018 and 2019 that includes (a) net amounts billed, unbilled receivables (overall), total receivables, contract costs (net) and deferred revenue (net); (b) the unbilled receivables split into aging buckets of ≤ 1 year, 1‑2 years, and 2‑5 years; and (c) calculated fields for year‑over‑year absolute changes, percentage changes for each line item, and the proportion of each aging bucket relative to the total unbilled receivables and to the other buckets. This dataset should enable queries on the evolution of receivable balances, the composition of unbilled receivables by maturity, and the relationship between contract costs and receivable trends.

Create a consolidated financial dataset for the Group covering fiscal years 2017/18 and 2018/19 that includes: (1) income‑statement items such as loss/profit before tax, adjusted profit before and after tax, trading profit, operating profit, adjusted EBITDA, earnings per share, depreciation, amortisation of intangibles, other non‑cash items, interest, taxation, pension contributions, restructuring costs, impairment, and any other non‑trading items; (2) cash‑flow statement figures including cash generated from operating activities, cash used in investing activities, cash (used in)/generated from financing activities, free cash flow, net increase in cash and cash equivalents, and related financing inflows/outflows; (3) divisional contribution data for Grocery and Sweet Treats, total group and corporate costs, and the resulting trading profit by segment; and (4) sufficient metadata to enable year‑over‑year comparisons, calculation of changes, averages, and percentage movements for all metrics. This dataset should support analysis of overall financial performance, identification of the key drivers behind the shift from profit to loss, and evaluation of segment‑level contributions and cost structures.

Provide a comprehensive, year‑by‑year dataset for TORM that includes all raw financial line items required to compute its alternative performance measures (e.g., operating profit, tax, EBIT, adjustments, adjusted operating profit, net debt, total equity, total invested capital, average invested capital, cash and cash equivalents, undrawn credit facilities, goodwill, intangible assets, property‑plant‑equipment, inventories, receivables, payables, etc.).  
Include pre‑calculated derived metrics such as RoIC, adjusted RoIC, return on invested capital, liquidity, average invested capital, average impairment, and average invested capital less average impairment, together with clear definitions and the formulas used for each metric.  
Enable calculation of absolute and percentage year‑over‑year changes for every raw component and derived metric, and allow identification of the years with the highest values for each measure.  
Support analysis of how individual components (e.g., net debt, impairment, adjustments, cash, credit facilities) drive the trends in RoIC, adjusted RoIC, and liquidity over time.

Compile a comprehensive dataset of Australian tax‑related financial figures for fiscal years 2017‑2019 that includes: (1) detailed yearly amounts for income tax (net of refunds), payroll tax, fringe benefits tax, and total taxes paid; (2) yearly values for subsidies and tax rebates, dividend income, net fair‑value gains on FVPL, net fair‑value gains on other financial instruments, donations, and other related items; and (3) the balance of unrecognized tax benefits at the beginning and end of each year together with all additions and reductions (including those for prior‑year positions, current‑year positions, statutory expirations, and acquisitions). The dataset should enable calculation of absolute and percentage changes year‑over‑year for each tax category, cash paid for income taxes (net of refunds), and the movements in unrecognized tax‑benefit balances.

Collect a comprehensive dataset covering the company’s stock‑based compensation and contingent purchase price information for fiscal years 2017‑2019. The dataset should include:  

- Grant‑date fair value per share and total grant‑date fair value of vested stock options for each year, as well as unrecognized compensation expense for unvested stock options, RSUs, and warrants, with the expected recognition periods.  
- Yearly operating cost breakdowns (cost of revenue, research & development, sales & marketing, general & administrative) and the total stock‑based compensation expense, enabling calculations of averages, year‑over‑year differences, and the percentage share of each cost component within total stock‑based compensation.  
- Valuation inputs used for equity awards (expected volatility, risk‑free interest rate, expected term in years, dividend yield) and the specific valuation models applied (e.g., Black‑Scholes for service‑based RSUs, market‑based PRSU model), together with any changes in these inputs between 2018 and 2019.  
- Entity‑level contingent purchase price payable figures for CareSpeak Communications and RMDY Health, including current fair value, long‑term fair value, total fair value, the proportion of long‑term to total, and year‑over‑year ratios and percentage changes.  

This data product should enable analysis of trends in equity compensation, cost composition, valuation methodology, and the financial impact of contingent purchase price obligations across the specified period and entities.

Compile a dataset of short‑term borrowings and the current portion of long‑term obligations that includes yearly (e.g., 2018, 2019 and subsequent years) line‑item amounts for the Euro term loan (current portion), the 1.3 % term loan due 2024, the 1.0 % State of Connecticut term loan due 2023, capital‑lease obligations, line‑of‑credit borrowings, as well as the aggregated totals for both the current portion and the full long‑term obligations; the data should enable comparison of each loan component across years, calculation of absolute and percentage changes (particularly for capital‑lease obligations), and identification of the years in which specific loan items were highest.

Collect a comprehensive dataset covering the company’s research and development financials for fiscal years 2018 and 2019 (including quarterly detail for Q4 2019), with the following elements: (1) all R&D funding sources, including government‑supported grants (e.g., Italy’s IPCEI program) and their associated locations; (2) line‑item expenses such as research and development funding, phase‑out and start‑up costs, exchange gains/losses, patent costs, gains on asset sales, and other net items, together with their values for each year and quarter; (3) detailed breakdowns of R&D expenses, capitalized development costs, amortization, impairments, and total R&D spend, plus percentages of each component relative to total R&D and to net revenues; (4) company‑sponsored R&D activity amounts by business unit (Cubic Transportation Systems, Cubic Mission Solutions, Cubic Global Defense, unallocated corporate expenses) and the overall total, with year‑over‑year changes and percentage changes; (5) summary metrics such as average values across 2018‑2019, absolute and percentage changes between years and quarters, and the drivers behind the increase in other income (e.g., higher R&D grants); and (6) contextual metadata on target markets, strategic cash reinvestment plans, and definitions of cost categories. The dataset should enable analysis of trends, variance, contribution of each R&D component to overall spend and revenue, and assessment of how government programs and business‑unit activities influence financial outcomes.

Collect a unified dataset covering American Tower Corporation’s capital expenditures from 2017‑2019 that includes: (1) the full real‑estate and accumulated depreciation schedule with yearly totals for additions, deductions, and ending balances, and a detailed breakdown of each addition type (acquisitions, discretionary capital projects, discretionary ground‑lease purchases, redevelopment capital expenditures, capital improvements, start‑up capital expenditures, other) and each deduction type (cost of real estate sold or disposed, other), together with clear definitions of these categories; (2) the Restaurants and Corporate Services capital‑expenditure details for the same years, listing restaurant facility expenditures, purchases of assets intended for sale or sale‑and‑leaseback, new restaurants, IT spending, other improvements, and total capital expenditures, plus the analogous line items for Corporate Services; (3) the Swedish‑segment figures for each year, showing total capital expenditures, the portion attributable to Sweden, and the share of annual sales; (4) all data should be formatted to enable calculation of year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes, identification of years where total additions exceed $1.5 billion or individual addition items exceed $200 million, and direct comparisons between Restaurants and Corporate Services expenditures as well as between the Swedish segment and overall totals; (5) include explanatory notes on the nature of discretionary capital projects, redevelopment expenditures, and any documented reasons for observed changes in capital spending.

Create a unified Bell Wireless operating metrics data product that (1) provides yearly blended ABPU ($/month) with its component exclusions, gross and net activation totals, churn percentages, and postpaid vs. prepaid breakdowns; (2) includes subscriber counts for all service categories (wireless postpaid, wireless prepaid, IPTV, Satellite, retail high‑speed Internet, retail TV, wireline residential lines, total services) together with year‑over‑year changes and percentage shares of each segment; and (3) captures consumer/SMB fiber revenue and subscriber figures (high‑speed Internet, video, voice) with total revenue across years, the proportion of enterprise‑fiber investment reflected in revenue, growth periods for entertainment and communications revenue, and regional fiber expansion details such as Hawaii.  

The dataset should enable analysis of subscriber adjustments, composition trends, revenue growth drivers, and investment efficiency across the entire Bell Wireless portfolio.

Collect a comprehensive EPS dataset for ON Semiconductor covering fiscal years 2018 and 2019 that includes: (1) net income attributable to the corporation; (2) basic and diluted weighted‑average common shares outstanding; (3) detailed incremental shares from share‑based awards, convertible notes, and Class A restricted‑stock‑unit shares; (4) the number of anti‑dilutive share‑based awards excluded each year; and (5) any other share‑count adjustments needed for EPS calculation. The dataset should enable calculation of basic and diluted earnings per share, year‑over‑year changes in net income and share counts, and the average net income across the two years.

Collect a comprehensive dataset on the company’s remaining performance obligations for non‑lease arrangements that includes, for each fiscal year:  

1. Segment‑level amounts (Zayo Networks, zColo, Allstream, and total) and identification of the segment with the highest amount.  
2. A breakdown of the obligations into deferred revenue, customer arrangements with termination rights, and estimated refund liabilities, together with year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes.  
3. Classification of the obligations by expected recognition timing (within one year vs. greater than one year) with yearly totals and changes.  
4. Service versus product deferred revenue details, showing current and non‑current portions, total amounts, and percentage changes year over year.  
5. Contract‑liability movements, including beginning‑of‑period balance, revenue deferred/acquired in the period, revenue recognized from contract liabilities, and end‑of‑period balance, plus calculated changes and percentages.  
6. Net deferred‑revenue components (deferred maintenance, other deferred revenue, total net, current portion, non‑current portion) with yearly values, year‑over‑year changes, and flags for years where amounts exceed $10,000 k.  
7. Pre‑computed indicators for years where specific segments or components exceed defined thresholds (e.g., Allstream > $10 M, other deferred revenue > $10,000 k) and the corresponding percentage changes.

The dataset should enable analysts to query across these dimensions, compare years, assess trends, and evaluate the impact of each component on the company’s future revenue recognition.

Compile a comprehensive dataset of VMware’s consolidated financial‑statement tax provision information for all reported fiscal years, including both current and deferred components broken down by jurisdiction (U.S. Federal, State, Non‑U.S., Foreign) and the corresponding income‑before‑taxs figures. The dataset should enable calculation of absolute and percentage year‑over‑year changes for each tax‑provision component and for the total provision, as well as identification of years where specific components exceed user‑defined monetary thresholds (e.g., total deferred > $1,000 k, current foreign > $200 M). It should also support queries that retrieve provision amounts for any selected year and jurisdiction, allowing direct comparison of current versus deferred provisions across U.S., Non‑U.S., and overall totals.

Collect a comprehensive dataset that includes, for each year 2017, 2018, and 2019, (1) net revenue, percentage of net revenue, contribution income, and contribution margin broken down by geographic region, (2) revenue, percentage of total net revenue, and contribution figures for each major customer group (contract manufacturers, consignment warehouses, distributors) and for the individual customers Flextronics Technology, Sanmina, Avnet Logistics, and Nexcomm, and (3) supporting fields that enable calculation of year‑over‑year changes, percentage changes, average revenues, and identification of the largest customers and regions, as well as detection of years when specific customers fall below defined percentage thresholds.

Create a unified dataset covering the company’s receivables and related allowance accounts for fiscal years 2017‑2019 that includes:  

1. Detailed allowance figures for doubtful accounts, sales‑return allowances, inventory‑return allowances, and deferred‑tax‑asset allowances, with itemized exclusions, total expense charges per year, and year‑over‑year percentage changes.  
2. A breakdown of trade receivables for each year (especially 2019) showing amounts not past‑due, the aging composition of past‑due balances (under 60 days, 60‑120 days, over 120 days), the total past‑due amount, its proportion of total receivables, and the policy for direct write‑offs to bad‑debt expense.  
3. A reconciliation from gross trade receivables to net trade receivables, listing all adjustments (allowances for doubtful accounts, stock‑rotation/ship‑from‑stock/debit, sales returns and discounts), the total allowance amount, the allowance‑as‑percentage‑of‑gross for each year, and the net‑receivables percentage change between 2018 and 2019.  

The dataset should enable queries that compute totals, percentages, and trends across these dimensions to support financial analysis of receivables quality and allowance effectiveness.

Compile a comprehensive dataset that consolidates all equity compensation plan information, including (1) approval status of each plan and the parties and award types eligible under approved and unapproved plans, (2) yearly figures for shares authorized, reserved for issuance, outstanding at the beginning and end of the year, grants, exercises, cancellations, and exercisable shares, (3) equity‑based compensation expense and the associated income‑tax benefits with year‑over‑year percentage changes, and (4) derived metrics such as the proportion of approved plans resulting in common‑stock versus RSU issuances, the percentage of outstanding subordinate shares available for issuance, and any other relevant ratios, to support analysis of plan utilization, stakeholder benefit, and financial impact.

Collect a comprehensive BIG W dataset covering FY18, FY19 and FY20 that includes (1) core financial performance metrics – sales, gross margin (%), cost of doing business (%), EBITDA, depreciation & amortisation, EBIT, LBIT (before and after significant items), funds employed, ROFE (%), sales per square metre, and related ratio fields (e.g., depreciation/amortisation as % of EBITDA, EBIT as % of EBITDA, EBIT‑to‑sales) – to enable trend analysis and calculation of nominal and percentage changes; (2) store‑footprint data – the number of Woolworths Supermarkets and Metro‑branded stores managed at year‑end – to assess the impact of store count on financial results; (3) detailed board and committee fee information – total board and committee fees, fees by each committee (People Performance, Sustainability, Audit & Risk, Nomination, etc.) and by individual members – to allow year‑over‑year comparison of governance costs; (4) shareholder‑return data – basic and diluted EPS (before and after significant items), total dividend per share with its interim, final and special components, and central overhead values – to evaluate earnings and dividend performance; (5) customer satisfaction metrics (VOC and NPS) for the same periods – to support correlation analysis between customer scores and financial outcomes; and (6) all necessary identifiers and timestamps so that analysts can compute nominal differences, percentage changes, and ratio analyses across the three fiscal years.

Create a consolidated, year‑level financial dataset that includes (1) unearned revenue components (license, subscription/SaaS, software maintenance, professional services) and total unearned revenue, with fields for absolute and percentage change between consecutive years and flags for when any component exceeds $5,000 million; (2) detailed operating revenue by product line (perpetual license, term license, maintenance, cloud, consulting) and total revenue, together with calculated year‑over‑year percentage changes for each line; (3) annual recurring revenue (ARR) metrics – total ARR, subscription ARR, and perpetual‑license‑support ARR – plus their year‑over‑year percentage changes and a count of years where total ARR exceeds $162 million; and (4) fiscal‑year revenue composition (subscription, maintenance, perpetual license, other, total) with the ability to compute the difference between subscription and maintenance revenue, the proportion of each component within total revenue, and the average maintenance revenue across selected years. The dataset should support queries that identify growth drivers, compare revenue streams across years, and highlight periods of significant change.

Collect a dataset of principal accounting fees and services that lists, for each fiscal year (e.g., 2018 and 2019), the amounts for audit fees, audit‑related fees, tax fees, all other fees, and the total fees, and includes clear definitions of each fee category; the data should support calculations of year‑over‑year changes (absolute and percentage), averages across years, and direct comparisons of fee amounts between years to identify which year had higher audit, tax, or other fees.

Create a consolidated GreenSky financial data product that includes, for each fiscal year (e.g., 2016‑2019), the full set of disclosed line items from the notes to the consolidated financial statements: beginning and ending balances, additions, proceeds, losses on sale, valuation allowance changes, transfers, write‑offs, total assets, net long‑term debt, equity, net sales, special charges, loss on debt settlement, net income from continuing operations, basic and diluted earnings per share, dividends, total other non‑operating expense, interest income, interest expense, gains/losses on derivative instruments, other financial items, income taxes, net income attributable to non‑controlling interests, detailed interest‑rate‑swap unrealized gain/loss (beginning balance, recognized OCI, ending balance), and the percentage of net revenue contributed by each major customer (e.g., Tech Data, Jenne, Westcon). The dataset should enable analysts to compute year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes, identify years where specific metrics exceed defined thresholds (e.g., additions > $100 M, total assets > $10 B), and perform attribution analysis to explain variations in interest income, non‑controlling interest results, and major‑customer revenue share. Include all necessary identifiers and timestamps to support these calculations and any future extensions.

Collect a comprehensive dataset covering the company’s operating performance for fiscal years 2018 and 2019 that includes: (1) total operating, services, and product revenues with detailed segment‑level breakdowns (Global Enterprise, Small & Medium Business, Wholesale, Consumer, International & Global Accounts, Enterprise, etc.) and sub‑category breakdowns (wireless, wireline data, wireline voice, media, other wireline services, broadcasting, network advertising, network distribution, etc.); (2) geographic revenue distribution (Americas, EMEA, Asia Pacific) and the corresponding percentage shares; (3) year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes for all revenue lines, total expenses, total margin, and margin percentage; (4) connection‑related metrics (total connections, post‑paid wireless, Fios internet/video, broadband, voice, net additions, churn rates) for each segment; (5) expense components and cost of providing services; and (6) documentation of revenue recognition policies for services and products.  The dataset should enable analysis of revenue trends, segment and geographic performance, drivers of revenue declines, and the relationship between connection metrics, churn, and financial outcomes.

Create a comprehensive dataset that includes, for each pension scheme category (e.g., overall scheme liabilities, smaller overseas schemes, premier schemes, RHm schemes, and combined schemes) and for the years 2018 and 2019: the discount rates applied, the RPI and CPI inflation assumptions, expected salary and pension increase percentages, the full breakdown of asset holdings (equities, government bonds, corporate bonds, property, absolute return products, cash, infrastructure funds, swaps, private equity, other) together with total assets, the corresponding liability amounts, and the discount‑rate‑based net present value of any future deficit payments. The dataset should support calculations of year‑over‑year changes in discount rates, inflation rates, asset class values, total assets, liabilities, and the net present value of deficits, as well as identification of the year with the higher CPI rate.

Collect a comprehensive dataset covering the company’s tax accounting for fiscal years 2018 and 2019 that includes: (1) the current tax provision broken down by Federal, Foreign, and State components and the total current provision; (2) the deferred (benefit) tax amounts and total provision; (3) income before income‑tax expense for U.S. and foreign operations; (4) non‑current tax provisions, specifically employee benefits and the dilapidation provision, together with their total non‑current provision; and (5) the enactment date of the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act. The dataset should enable calculation of year‑over‑year changes, percentage changes, averages, and the percentage composition of foreign taxes within the current provision and employee benefits within the total non‑current provision.

Compile a consolidated, multi‑year cash‑flow dataset that includes detailed operating, investing, financing, and supplemental cash‑flow items (e.g., software, computer hardware, leasehold improvements, furniture, purchases of property/equipment/software, non‑cash investing and financing activities, capital expenditures incurred but not paid, interest paid, income taxes paid, foreign‑currency effects, and total cash‑flow aggregates) together with partnership profit/(loss) allocation figures (common unitholders, general partner, IDRs, paid and accrued preference equity distributions, allocations to GasLog and non‑controlling interests). The dataset should cover every fiscal year present in the source tables (e.g., 2017‑2019), provide both absolute values and enable calculation of year‑over‑year and percentage changes for all line items, support queries to flag years where specific amounts exceed user‑defined thresholds, and include metadata on the cash‑flow statement version and source reference for traceability.

Collect a comprehensive dataset covering the 2020 Incentive Plan Enhancements that includes:  

1. All short‑term and long‑term incentive plan metrics added in 2020, the rationale for each addition, and the count of metrics per plan.  
2. The performance‑level framework (Maximum, Target, Threshold, Below Threshold), associated payout percentages, and the linear‑interpolation rules used to calculate payout as a % of the target award.  
3. Adjusted EBITDA targets, run‑rate calculations, cumulative Adjusted EBITDA (2‑ and 3‑year), and Relative TSR Modifiers for the relevant periods.  
4. Segment‑level Adjusted EBITDA (International and Global Accounts, Enterprise, Small and Medium Business, Wholesale, Consumer) and total adjusted EBITDA for each fiscal year, with year‑over‑year change values.  
5. Full statement‑of‑income data for the years covered (Revenue, Cost of Sales, Gross Profit, Administrative Costs, Operating Profit before exceptional items, Impairment loss, Net profit/loss, EPS, etc.), enabling computation of absolute and percentage changes across years.  
6. Definitions of EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA, and a detailed list of items excluded from Adjusted EBITDA (integration and transformation costs, special items, and any other excluded expenses).  

The dataset should be structured to support analysis of metric additions, target adjustments, segment performance trends, revenue and profit growth, and the effect of performance‑level thresholds on incentive payouts.

Compile a comprehensive dataset of the company’s deferred tax assets and liabilities that includes, for each reporting year, a detailed breakdown by component (net operating loss carryforwards, R&D carryovers, depreciation, stock‑based compensation, other items, and valuation allowance) and by jurisdiction (U.S. federal, state, Canadian provincial, foreign), together with the scheduled expiration windows for each NOL category (e.g., 2020‑2024, 2025‑2029, etc.). The dataset should enable calculation of year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes for each component, the proportion of each component within total deferred tax assets, comparative ratios and differences between jurisdictions and expiration periods (e.g., Federal vs. State NOLs, Federal vs. Foreign NOL ratios), and aggregation of total net deferred tax assets and total NOL balances.

Collect a comprehensive, year‑by‑year dataset of the company's Accumulated Other Comprehensive Income (AOCI) and related deferred‑tax items that includes: (1) line‑item amounts for unrealized losses on available‑for‑sale securities, amortization of actuarial losses, and reclassifications of realized transactions (net of taxes); (2) the gross and net amounts of deductible temporary differences, tax credits, and unrecognized deferred tax assets, together with the ability to compute ratios and percentages between these figures; and (3) a detailed breakdown of deferred tax assets and liabilities—including inventory valuation, net operating loss carryforwards, capital loss carryforwards, share‑based compensation, income tax credits, property, plant and equipment, accrued expenses, intangible assets, other items, convertible debt, and associated valuation allowances—along with gross, net, and valuation‑allowance values. The dataset should support queries that retrieve values for any reporting year, identify the years covered, calculate absolute and percentage changes between years, and derive any requested ratios or percentages across the various components.

Collect a multi‑year dataset that consolidates all common‑stock activity, including beginning balances, shares issued through stock options, employee stock purchase plans, restricted‑stock vesting, performance‑stock unit awards, stock‑leverage opportunity awards, acquisitions, cancellations, tax netting, and other adjustments, together with treasury‑stock repurchases and holdings; provide ending balances for both treasury shares and total common shares outstanding for each fiscal year, and include enough granularity to compute year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes, the proportion of treasury shares to total outstanding shares, and the specific contribution of each compensation program to overall share dilution.

1. Compile a dataset covering the company's goodwill balances for each fiscal year from 2015 through 2019, including beginning‑of‑period amounts, goodwill added through acquisitions (e.g., Golden Ridge in 2018 and MGI in 2019), impairments, and ending‑of‑period values, together with calculated year‑over‑year changes and percentage variations.  

2. Provide the total goodwill generated by acquisitions for each year and the net difference between acquisition goodwill amounts across years.  

3. Express goodwill as a share of total assets, cash and equivalents, total stockholders’ equity, and long‑term debt for each year, and indicate the proportion of goodwill attributable to specific business segments or Level‑3 classifications.  

4. Include related financial metrics from Note 9 such as adjusted EBITDA, cash taxes, maintenance and corporate capex, gross PPE, gross intangibles, gross goodwill (with a clear definition of what is excluded), and ROIC for the same years, enabling correlation analysis between goodwill levels and operating performance.  

5. Document any accounting adjustments, reclassifications (e.g., assets held for sale), the composition of long‑term debt, and the number of years where gross intangibles exceeded $15 billion, to support comprehensive trend and variance analysis.

Collect a comprehensive dataset that captures the company’s balance‑sheet and related financial line items before and after ASC 606 adoption, including (i) current and non‑current assets (trade receivables, related‑party receivables, prepaid expenses, computer software, deferred contract costs, voyage receivables, etc.), (ii) current and non‑current liabilities (deferred revenue, other accrued liabilities, long‑term deferred revenue, deferred income taxes, etc.), and (iii) equity components (accumulated deficit, retained earnings). Provide the balances for the specific dates February 28 2018, March 1 2018, January 31 2018, January 31 2019, and year‑end 2017‑2019, together with the corresponding ASC 605 figures where applicable. Enable calculations of (a) absolute and percentage differences between pre‑ and post‑adoption balances (e.g., deferred tax assets vs. deferred revenue, total assets vs. total liabilities, current vs. non‑current deferred revenue), (b) key financial ratios such as the current ratio and equity‑to‑total‑equity‑and‑liabilities, and (c) the share of unbilled deferred revenue in total revenue and its quarterly/annual change. Include explanatory fields that allow analysis of drivers behind quarterly variations in billed versus unbilled deferred revenue and the overall impact of ASC 606 on net cash provided by financing activities. The dataset should support trend analysis, ratio computation, and comparative reporting across the fiscal years surrounding the ASC 606 transition.

Compile a comprehensive property‑and‑equipment dataset that includes, for each fiscal year (minimum 2018 and 2019), the gross amounts and net values (after accumulated depreciation/amortization) of all asset categories such as land, land improvements, buildings and improvements, leasehold improvements, machinery & equipment, computers/data‑processing equipment, software, furniture & fixtures, vehicles, construction‑in‑process, and other items. Include the estimated useful life for each asset category and the accumulated depreciation figures. Provide the data in a structured format that allows users to calculate average balances across the two years, compare year‑over‑year amounts (identifying which year has higher balances for specific assets), compute absolute and percentage changes (e.g., for leasehold improvements), and analyze differences in useful‑life estimates between categories (e.g., buildings vs. furniture & fixtures). Also include metadata describing how the property‑and‑equipment information is presented in the source tables and the years covered.

Collect a comprehensive dataset of the company’s contract‑balance items for fiscal years 2018 and 2019, including unbilled receivables, customer receivables (gross and net of allowance for doubtful accounts), contract assets, contract liabilities (current and non‑current, with a breakdown of deferred revenue components), and net contract assets/liabilities.  
Provide year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes for each balance‑sheet line item, as well as the average values across the two years.  
Calculate and include key performance ratios such as unbilled receivables to total revenue, contract liabilities to revenue, and days sales outstanding based on payment terms.  
Document the composition of contract liabilities and the methodology used to recognize revenue from those liabilities.

Collect a comprehensive, year‑by‑year dataset for American Tower Corporation and its subsidiaries covering fiscal years 2017‑2019 that includes (a) gross cost, accumulated depreciation, and net book value for each asset class (land, buildings, leasehold improvements, machinery and equipment, computer/R&D equipment, other tangible assets, construction in progress), (b) detailed depreciation and amortization figures broken out by geographic segment (AMER, APAC, EMEA, Corporate) and by component (standard depreciation, amortization, depreciation of right‑of‑use assets), and (c) all additions, disposals, other adjustments, and beginning/ending balances of accumulated depreciation. The dataset should also capture any policy changes or specific transactions (e.g., Norstel acquisition) that affect asset recognition, enabling analysis of yearly depreciation trends, percentage changes, average costs, and the impact of regional and asset‑type variations on total depreciation and amortization.

Compile a comprehensive financial dataset for the fiscal years ending December 31, 2018 and December 31, 2019 that includes detailed revenue breakdowns (products & licensing, technology development, fixed‑fee license, per‑unit royalty, total royalty & license, development/services, total revenues) and expense categories (cost of revenues, sales & marketing, research & development, general & administrative, restructuring, total costs & expenses) together with operating income, interest, other income/expenses, pre‑tax income, tax provision, and net income. The dataset should enable: (1) year‑over‑year comparison of each revenue and expense line to quantify increases or decreases; (2) identification of the primary drivers behind changes in technology development revenue, products & licensing revenue, and total revenues; (3) calculation of average values for key revenue items across the two years; and (4) analysis of how shifts in cost structures contributed to the observed decline in operating and net income.

Create a unified dataset that (1) lists the company’s unaudited quarterly service‑revenue amounts for Q1‑Q4 2018 and provides fields for total service‑revenue, average quarterly service‑revenue, and quarter‑over‑quarter percentage change; (2) records the annual total revenue, subscription‑solutions revenue, and merchant‑solutions revenue for the years ended December 31 2018 and 2019, enabling year‑over‑year change calculations and identification of the highest‑earning revenue segment; (3) includes the cost‑of‑revenues breakdown—cost of subscription solutions, cost of merchant solutions, and total cost of revenues—for both 2018 and 2019, together with each cost component’s percentage of total revenue, to allow comparison of cost structures across the two years; and (4) derives additional metrics such as total yearly revenue, cost‑to‑revenue ratios, and flags the year with the highest total revenue and the year with the highest total cost.

Collect a comprehensive, year‑by‑year financial dataset for A10 Networks, Inc. covering the audited periods from 2015 through 2019 that includes: (1) net revenues, net sales, cost of goods sold, gross profit, operating income (loss), loss from operations, other income/expenses, interest expense, loss before income taxes, income tax expense, net loss (total and attributable to common stockholders), and comprehensive loss components (including unrealized gains/losses on marketable securities); (2) basic and diluted net loss per share, basic and diluted shares used in per‑share calculations; (3) detailed expense line items such as depreciation expense, plant start‑up expense, and non‑cash share‑based compensation, together with adjusted gross profit and its percentage of net sales; and (4) the units for all monetary values (thousands of dollars) and per‑share amounts. The dataset should be structured to support calculations of year‑over‑year percentage changes, cumulative totals across multiple years (e.g., total unrealized gains 2017‑2019, total comprehensive loss 2017‑2019), and profitability ratios, enabling analysis of trends, expense impacts, and share‑based performance metrics.

Create a comprehensive dataset of the company's deferred tax assets and deferred tax liabilities for fiscal years 2018 and 2019 that includes the dollar amount (in thousands) for each line‑item component (e.g., reserve for uncollectible accounts, accrued vacation pay, accrued expenses, deferred revenue, tax credit carryforwards, goodwill and other intangibles, stock‑based compensation, lease‑related temporary differences, investment tax credits, etc.), the associated valuation allowance, and the resulting net totals. The dataset should enable users to (1) retrieve any specific component value for either year, (2) calculate absolute and percentage changes for each component between 2018 and 2019, (3) compute average total deferred tax assets and liabilities across the two years, (4) identify which year had the highest total deferred tax assets, and (5) assess the criteria that determine whether deferred tax assets are realizable (including valuation allowance application).

Gather pro forma consolidated results of operations for fiscal years 2018 and 2019, including Revenue and Income from continuing operations, to enable calculation of year‑over‑year revenue changes, average revenue, identification of any year with revenue below $65 million, and comparison of income from continuing operations across the years.  
Also collect the detailed acquisition‑related expense data for the same periods—transaction‑related expenses, integration and transformation‑related expenses, and total acquisition‑related expenses—to support analysis of cumulative and per‑category expenses, compute absolute and percentage changes in total acquisition‑related expenses between 2018 and 2019, and determine which year incurred the lowest total acquisition‑related expense.

Create a comprehensive Navios Maritime Holdings financial data product that includes, for each fiscal year (at least 2018‑2025):  

- Segment‑level revenue and “minimum revenue, net of commissions” for the dry‑bulk vessel and logistics businesses, plus the total minimum revenue across all segments.  
- Gross‑profit figures for each operating segment (e.g., PSG, ASG, ISG) and the aggregate gross profit, together with unallocated manufacturing costs.  
- Key income‑statement items (total revenue, administrative‑fee revenue from affiliates, interest income, interest expense, depreciation & amortization, equity in earnings of affiliates, net income attributable to Navios Holdings) and balance‑sheet items (total assets, goodwill, capital expenditures, investment in affiliates, cash & cash equivalents, restricted cash, long‑term debt).  
- Product and service gross‑profit amounts, their percentages of product and service revenues, and the year‑over‑year percentage changes for both categories.  

The dataset should be structured to allow analysts to:  

1. Track and compare revenue and minimum‑revenue trends for dry‑bulk and logistics segments across years, and calculate inter‑segment and inter‑year differences.  
2. Analyze gross‑profit performance by segment, compute year‑over‑year changes, and derive average gross profit for selected periods.  
3. Examine overall financial health by comparing revenue, interest income, goodwill, and investment in affiliates, and assess how these metrics differ between the dry‑bulk and logistics operations.  
4. Evaluate the contribution and growth of product versus service profitability, including percentage of revenue and change rates.  

The data product should be delivered in a normalized, query‑friendly format (e.g., relational tables or a multi‑sheet spreadsheet) with clear identifiers for year, segment, and metric.

Collect a comprehensive dataset of the company’s “Business Segments” financials for fiscal years 2017, 2018, and 2019 that includes, for each segment (Provider, Veradigm, Unallocated Amounts, corporate/others, probe‑cards, etc.), the revenue, gross profit, gross margin %, income from operations, and operating margin %. Provide total figures for each year, calculate year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes for all metrics at both the segment and company‑wide levels, and indicate each segment’s share of total revenue and gross profit. Include any available explanatory attributes (e.g., volume, pricing, cost components) that allow analysis of the underlying drivers behind increases or decreases in revenue, gross profit, margins, and operating income across the three‑year period.

Collect a comprehensive dataset of Proofpoint, Inc.’s post‑acquisition balance‑sheet items as disclosed in the Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements, including fair‑value amounts for every current‑asset, fixed‑asset, and intangible line item (customer relationships, order backlog, core/developed technology, trade name, in‑process research & development, goodwill) as well as all liability categories (operating‑lease liabilities, deferred revenue, other liabilities, deferred tax liability). Capture the valuation method used for each acquired intangible, record the estimated useful life for each intangible and identify the asset with the longest useful life, and provide acquisition‑related cash‑flow details (net cash acquired, deferred cash consideration, deferred shares) together with the specific forfeiture conditions for the deferred shares. Compute and include summary metrics such as the difference between current‑asset and fixed‑asset fair values, average fair values for customer relationships and core/developed technology, total fair value of all assets, total fair value of all tangible assets, and total goodwill fair value. This dataset should enable analysis of asset composition, valuation approaches, useful‑life implications, and acquisition financing terms.

Compile a comprehensive dataset of the company’s senior unsecured notes and related financing arrangements that includes, for each note series and tranche, the issue date, maturity date, fixed annual interest rate, aggregate principal amount, fair value, remaining amortization period, unamortized issuance costs, current portion, and any cash‑flow events such as repurchases, redemptions, prepayments, settled and unsettled conversions. Enable calculations of (a) the absolute and percentage change in total long‑term debt year‑over‑year, (b) each tranche’s share of total notes outstanding, (c) identification of the series with the highest interest rate, the note with the highest fair value, and the note with the longest remaining amortization, and (d) custom ratios and differences such as the increase in carrying value of one note relative to another and cash differences between selected tranches. This dataset should support queries and analyses that address all of the listed user questions and facilitate broader assessments of debt structure, cost of capital, and financing risk.

Collect a multi‑year (e.g., 2017‑2019) dataset that consolidates the company’s statements of operations and financing, including line items such as net sales, cost of sales, selling‑general‑administrative expenses, research & development, restructuring charges, total operating costs, operating income, net income, adjusted EBITDA, depreciation & amortization, equity‑based compensation, tax expense, non‑recurring expenses, other income/expense, and a detailed breakdown of interest expense and interest income (overall and by each debt instrument and senior‑note series, plus capitalized interest and net interest). The dataset should enable calculation of year‑over‑year absolute and percentage changes for these metrics, identification of years where metrics exceed defined thresholds (e.g., net income > $100 M, interest income > $1.5 M, interest expense > $50 M), and analysis of the drivers behind changes in interest expense and other income/expense items.

Collect a comprehensive profitability dataset for the company covering fiscal years 2017‑2020 that includes: (1) segment‑level Adjusted EBITDA for each business unit (Telematics Systems, Software & Subscription Services, Satellite, etc.) and the total Adjusted EBITDA per year; (2) detailed corporate expense amounts and average corporate expense per year; (3) explanatory fields on factors influencing EBITDA changes such as revenue variations, margin impacts, and other operational drivers; (4) debt‑related metrics for each year, including average cost of indebtedness, fixed‑rate indebtedness, average term of long‑term debt, net indebtedness to Adjusted EBITDA, and Adjusted EBITDA to financial expense; and (5) operational context variables such as months of operations, net cash consideration, and management EBITDA projections. The dataset should enable year‑over‑year comparisons, driver analysis of EBITDA fluctuations, and assessment of the relationship between financing costs and profitability.

Compile a comprehensive, year‑by‑year dataset on the company’s long‑term debt for fiscal 2018 and 2019 that includes:  

1. Net long‑term debt broken down by current maturities, interest‑free notes and any other components, with the absolute amounts for each year and the percentage or absolute changes between the years.  
2. Details of notes payable and loans secured by trade receivables – issuance dates, currencies, hedging methods, total debt due within one year, weighted‑average interest rates, and the difference in weighted‑average rates between the two categories.  
3. Information on debt derivatives related to senior notes – number settled in 2019, repayment due dates, hedge interest rates (e.g., April 30 2019), coupon‑rate adjustments between issuance dates, equivalent‑currency amounts (e.g., CAD equivalents) and the average principal/notional amount for 2019.  
4. US‑dollar‑denominated long‑term borrowings – total amount, percentage hedged, hedged exchange rate, amount and percentage of borrowings at fixed rates, total borrowings, weighted‑average interest rate, weighted‑average term to maturity, and the year‑over‑year changes in US‑dollar‑denominated debt and total borrowings.  

The dataset should enable calculation of all requested absolute values, differences, and percentage changes across the two years.

Create a consolidated dataset for the Deferred Compensation Plan covering fiscal years 2018 and 2019 that includes detailed line‑item values for all asset components (cash surrender value of corporate‑owned life insurance, fair value of mutual and money‑market funds, other long‑term assets), every liability category (short‑term debt and current maturities of long‑term debt, trade payables, other current financial liabilities, contract liabilities, provisions, current and long‑term tax liabilities, deferred tax liabilities, other long‑term liabilities, deferred compensation liabilities, etc.), and the related equity figures. The dataset should enable analysts to calculate absolute and percentage year‑over‑year changes for each line item, identify which year had higher totals for assets, liabilities, and specific categories, and support analysis of the drivers behind changes such as contributions, guarantees, tax adjustments, and debt movements.

Collect a comprehensive dataset that includes the Consolidated Statement of Operations and the Balance Sheet for the fiscal year ended August 31 2019 both as reported and as they would appear without the adoption of ASU 2014‑09, providing line‑item values for net revenue, cost of revenue, operating income, income tax expense, net income, contract assets, inventories (net), prepaid expenses and other current assets, deferred income taxes, contract liabilities, deferred income, other accrued expenses, and retained earnings; the dataset should enable calculation of absolute differences, ratios (e.g., operating income to reported amount), percentage changes for each item, and allow identification of any business segments whose reported figures exceed $2 billion.

Collect a unified, quarter‑level dataset of Jabil Inc.’s unaudited financial results (covering at least FY 2017‑FY 2019) that includes for each quarter: net revenue, gross profit, operating income (loss), net (loss) income, provision for income taxes, distressed customer charges, basic and diluted earnings per share, and any other disclosed line items. The dataset should enable users to retrieve any metric for a specific quarter, compute absolute and percentage changes between any two quarters, sum revenues or other metrics across selected quarters, and count quarters that meet criteria such as operating income exceeding $150 million (i.e., $150,000 thousand).

Collect a unified dataset covering the company’s equity‑investment and interest‑and‑other financial results for fiscal years 2017, 2018, and 2019, including the following line‑item amounts (in millions): ongoing mark‑to‑market adjustments on marketable equity securities, observable price adjustments on non‑marketable equity securities, impairment charges, sales of equity investments and other, gains (losses) on equity investments, net interest and other income/expense, interest income, interest expense, other income, foreign‑currency gains (losses), gains (losses) on strategic investments, gains on deferred‑compensation plan assets, gains (losses) on extinguishment of debt, and any other net items reported.  

Enable analysis that: (1) identifies the main drivers of year‑over‑year changes in net gains/losses for both equity‑investment and interest‑and‑other categories; (2) calculates the proportion of specific components (e.g., impairment charges, dividend sales) relative to their total categories; (3) computes percentage changes, averages, and totals for each line‑item across the three‑year period; and (4) supports narrative explanations of observed trends such as increases in interest income, losses on strategic investments, or foreign‑currency effects.

Create a comprehensive, year‑by‑year dataset for Note 8 “Goodwill and Intangible Assets, Net” that includes:  

1. The opening and closing balances for each intangible‑asset component (e.g., goodwill, customer relationships, ACI on‑demand, other indefinite‑lived intangibles) for every fiscal year covered, together with the amortization expense, additions from business combinations, impairments, and derecognitions for each component.  

2. The total balance of all intangible assets at the beginning and end of each year, and the ability to calculate absolute and percentage changes between consecutive years (e.g., 2018 → 2019, 2019 → 2020).  

3. Counts of asset and liability line items whose balances exceed user‑specified thresholds (e.g., assets > $1 billion, intangible components > $50 million, liabilities > $300 million) for each reporting date.  

4. The corresponding balances for major balance‑sheet categories (accounts receivable, inventories, other current assets, long‑term deferred tax assets, other assets, accrued liabilities, deferred income, long‑term liabilities, stockholders’ equity items) on the same dates, to support cross‑analysis of how changes in intangible assets relate to overall financial position.  

The dataset should be structured to allow straightforward queries for individual values, year‑over‑year changes, percentage changes, and threshold‑based counts across all provided tables.

Create a comprehensive backlog data product that includes (a) total backlog and its segment breakdown (Cubic Transportation Systems, Cubic Mission Solutions, Cubic Global Defense) with yearly and quarterly values to calculate absolute and percentage changes and identify drivers of any decreases; (b) yearly figures for backlog at the beginning of the year, new orders, revenue, FX‑effect, IFRS‑15 adjustments, and the resulting book‑to‑bill ratio, enabling analysis of how new bookings and financial adjustments affect backlog dynamics; (c) ACI On Premise and ACI On Demand backlog components (committed and renewal) captured at the reporting dates of March 31, June 30, September 30, and December 31 2019, allowing month‑to‑month and quarter‑to‑quarter comparisons; and (d) the 60‑month backlog estimate attributable to the Speedpay acquisition, so its impact can be isolated and assessed. The dataset should be structured to support calculations of trends, percentages, and segment contributions across all these dimensions.

Compile a comprehensive dataset that includes financial metrics such as gross profit, gross margin, cost of revenue, and net sales, and allows for the analysis of changes in these metrics over time, the identification of factors contributing to these changes, and the evaluation of relationships between different financial metrics, to support the assessment of financial performance and inform strategic business decisions.

Compile a dataset that will allow queries on share option values, including expected term, risk-free interest rate, expected volatility, and expected dividend yield, across different years. The data should support analysis of trends and changes in these values over time, as well as calculations of averages and percentages. It should also enable evaluation of the relationships between these factors and their impact on share option pricing.

Compile a dataset that will allow queries on income tax expenses, including federal and state income taxes, effective tax rates, and the impact of various factors such as the Tax Act, stock compensation, and changes in valuation allowance. The data should support analysis of trends and patterns in income tax expenses over time, comparison of tax expenses across different years and categories, and identification of the factors that influence these expenses.

Also, gather data on the company's relationships with related parties, including services provided and received, and receivables and liabilities from these services. The data should support analysis of the company's financial performance and position, as well as the impact of various factors on its cash flow and profitability.

Gather data on the pension expenses of the direct and indirect company pension plan commitments, including the breakdown of these expenses into components such as current service cost, net interest expenses, past service cost, settlements, other pension expenses, and pension expenses. Also, compile data on the cost of sales, selling, general and administrative expenses, other expenses, deferred tax assets, and deferred tax liabilities. The data should allow for queries on the changes in these expenses over the years and the years in which these expenses were recorded. This will enable an analysis of the trends in pension expenses and their impact on the company's financial performance.

Gather data on the components of deferred tax assets and liabilities for multiple companies, and analyze how changes in these components impact the companies' financial position over time. The analysis should cover factors such as employee benefits, tax loss and credit carry forwards, depreciation, and valuation allowances, as well as the impact of specific events such as the adoption of IFRS 15 or state tax rate changes. The data product should provide insights into the drivers of changes in deferred tax assets and liabilities, and how these changes impact the companies' overall financial performance.

Gather data on a company's income taxes, both domestic and foreign, for multiple years and analyze the trends and changes in these taxes over time. Additionally, analyze the company's other income and expenses, such as interest income and foreign exchange gains or losses, and their impact on the company's total income before income taxes. Finally, analyze the company's total income before income taxes and the components of this income, such as domestic and foreign income, and the changes in this income over time.

Gather data on the research and development expenses of the company over the past few years, and analyze the trends, changes, and reasons for these changes. Additionally, assess the impact of these expenses on the company's revenues and identify any significant components contributing to these expenses.

Gather data on the company's pension and other benefit obligations, including the trend rates for Canadian post-retirement plans and the respective pension discount rates for actuarial benefit obligation and benefit costs. Analyze the significant assumptions adopted in measuring these obligations, such as service costs, interest costs, expected return on plan assets, and amortization of actuarial gains and losses. Provide insights into the net periodic pension cost, net actuarial gain (loss), amendments, and settlement and curtailment loss (gain). Lastly, provide an analysis of the total pre-tax retirement-related plan cost and the net pension (benefit) cost.

Gather financial data for a business from 2018 to 2019, including information on common shares, net operating loss carryforwards, stock options, restricted stock units, and other financial metrics. Analyze the data to identify trends, changes, and averages in these metrics over the two-year period, and provide insights into the financial health and performance of the business.

Gather data on the shipping industry's performance measures, including revenue, expenses, and TCE earnings, and analyze the components of revenue, changes in TCE earnings, and the factors contributing to these changes. The data should also cover the performance of different types of carriers and the impact of various expenses on overall performance.

Gather data on the systems revenue, hardware revenue, and software revenue of a company, and analyze the factors contributing to the changes in revenue and profitability from year to year. Additionally, assess the performance of specific hardware platforms, such as IBM Z, Power Systems, and Storage Systems, and identify the drivers of their growth or decline.

Gather data on the fair value and carrying amounts of various financial instruments, including notes payable and long-term debt, derivative financial instruments, tax receivables, and other liabilities, and analyze the changes in these values over time. Additionally, provide insights into the reasons behind the carrying amount being a reasonable approximation of fair value and the information contained in relevant notes.

Gather data on the consolidated net revenues of the company, broken down by distribution channels (digital online, retail, and other), platforms (console, PC, mobile and ancillary, and other), and segments (Activision, Blizzard, and King). Analyze the trends in net revenues from these different sources over the years, and assess the contribution of each channel, platform, and segment to the total consolidated net revenues. Additionally, evaluate the segment operating income of different segments and the differences in net revenues from external customers between Activision and Blizzard.

Gather data on net debt, including IFRS 16 lease liabilities, for various companies, and analyze trends in total liabilities, total capital, and other financial metrics over time. Assess the impact of changes in these metrics on the companies' financial leverage and capital structure, and identify any patterns or relationships that emerge from the analysis.

Gather data on trade and other payables, including current and non-current payables, trade payables, accruals, taxes, and other payables, for multiple years. Analyze the changes in these components over time, calculate percentage changes, and identify the years in which certain components were larger. Additionally, provide insights into the conditions and recognition of trade payables, and explain why certain amounts are considered to be the same as their fair value.

Gather data on the net income per share of VMware, Inc. for various years, and analyze the trends and changes in net income, weighted-average shares, basic and diluted earnings per share, and other related metrics. Assess the impact of factors such as restructuring costs, U.S. tax reform, and one-time employee bonuses on the diluted earnings per share.

Gather data on the earnings per share (EPS) of a company, including both basic and diluted EPS calculations, and analyze the trends in the weighted-average number of shares of common stock outstanding over time. Additionally, assess the impact of potential common stock associated with stock options and other dilutive securities on the EPS calculations. The data should also support an evaluation of the company's performance in terms of income from continuing operations and the effects of potential common stock determined using the treasury stock method.

Gather data on the year-on-year changes in cost of revenues and revenues for each line of business (VAS, FinTech and Business Services, Online Advertising, and Others) and analyze the primary reasons for these changes. Additionally, provide insights into the profit margins for each quarter and the proportion of profits attributable to equity holders of the company.

Gather financial data for multiple companies, including their gross payment volume, adjusted revenue, adjusted EBITDA, adjusted net income, non-GAAP operating income, non-GAAP revenue, net sales, cost of sales, gross margin, non-GAAP gross profit, non-GAAP operating loss, non-GAAP net loss, and free cash flow. Analyze the financial performance of these companies over multiple years, comparing key financial metrics and identifying trends. Additionally, assess the impact of non-GAAP measures on the financial results and provide insights into how these measures aid investors in understanding the financial health of the companies.

Compile a dataset that will allow queries on interest expense and its components, including interest before impact of interest rate caps, impact of interest rate caps, average daily utilization, weighted average interest rate, senior secured notes interest, bank debt interest, and other related costs. The data should cover multiple years to allow for trend analysis and comparison. The dataset should support insights into the changes in interest expense over time, the factors contributing to these changes, and the average values of different components of interest expense.

Gather data on the impact of adopting Topic 606 on various assets and liabilities of a company, including contract assets, inventories, accounts receivable, contract liabilities, and retained earnings. The data should also include the tax impact associated with the adoption of Topic 606. The data should be able to provide insights into the percentage changes in these balances due to the adoption of Topic 606.

Compile a dataset that will allow queries on the company's financial liabilities and assets, including other liabilities, other financial assets and liabilities, and lease liabilities. The data should provide insights into the trends and changes in these financial aspects from 2018 to 2019, including average values, percentages, and comparisons between current and non-current liabilities. The data should also support an analysis of the company's financial health and performance, including the constitution of its total liabilities and assets.

Gather data on the company's investment portfolio, including the composition of assets, their fair values, amortized costs, and unrealized gains or losses. Analyze the trends in investment in various asset categories such as cash and cash equivalents, equity securities, government debt securities, corporate debt securities, investments in funds, real estate, and other assets. Additionally, assess the changes in investment in these categories over time and the impact of these investments on the company's total assets.

Gather data on deferred tax assets and liabilities for multiple years, and analyze the components of these accounts, changes in these accounts over time, and the relationship between different components. The data should also support queries on specific items under deferred tax assets and liabilities, and calculations of changes and percentages related to these items.

Gather data on VMware's financial transactions and arrangements with Dell, including purchases and leases of products and services, Dell subsidiary support and administrative costs, reseller revenue, internal-use revenue, and collaborative technology project receipts. Analyze the trends and changes in these financial aspects over multiple years, and assess how these transactions and arrangements have evolved between VMware and Dell.

Analyze the financial performance and obligations of the company's retirement plans, including pension and post-retirement benefit plans, by examining changes in accrued benefit liabilities, actuarial losses and gains, prior service costs, and deferred income tax benefits and expenses over time, and assess their impact on the company's comprehensive income and accumulated other comprehensive loss.

Gather data on the company's financial performance from 2017 to 2019, disaggregated by the major markets it serves, its segments (EMS and DMS), and its products and services. Analyze the trends in revenue, segment performance, and product line performance, and identify the factors contributing to the company's financial growth or decline.

Gather financial data for multiple years, including revenue, operating expenses, EBITDA, and exchange rates, and analyze the trends in these metrics over time. Additionally, assess the impact of exchange rates on financial performance and identify any significant changes in performance indicators.

Gather data on the company's environmental impact, including greenhouse gas emissions, waste production, and energy consumption, across different locations and scopes. Analyze trends over time, compare emissions and waste production between locations, and identify factors contributing to changes in environmental impact. Additionally, calculate and track carbon intensity and intensity ratios to understand the company's environmental performance relative to its revenue and billings.

Gather data on the remuneration and fees paid to auditors and other service providers by various companies, and analyze the trends in audit fees, audit-related fees, tax fees, and other fees over time. Assess the impact of these fees on the companies' financials and the services provided by different auditors. Additionally, evaluate the changes in the fees paid to auditors and the services they provide, and their implications for the companies' financial health.

Gather data on the company's uncertain tax positions, including the beginning and ending balances, additions and reductions for tax positions related to prior and current years, and the impact of statute of limitations and settlements with tax authorities. Analyze the changes in these balances over time and identify the factors contributing to these changes, such as business acquisitions, foreign currency translation, and tax rate re-measurement. Additionally, assess the potential impact of these uncertain tax positions on the company's effective tax rate and financial statements.

Gather data on unrecognized tax benefits and their impact on deferred tax assets from 2017 to 2019, and analyze the factors contributing to changes in these benefits, including additions for tax positions of prior and current periods, reductions due to settlements and lapses, and the impact of tax litigations and uncertain tax positions. Additionally, assess the trends in accrued interest and penalties over this period.

Gather data on the company's interest expense and debt obligations, including debt issuance amortization, debt discount amortization, and other interest expenses, over the years. Analyze the trends and changes in these components and provide insights into the company's debt principal, unamortized discount, and net carrying amount of convertible debt. Also, compile data on the company's long-term debt and capital lease obligations to understand the company's financial position better.

Gather data on the company's gross unrecognized tax benefits, additions, reductions, and balances for the years 2018 and 2019, and analyze how these factors impact the company's effective income tax rate and financial position. Additionally, assess the changes in balances and additions over the years and identify any trends or patterns that may influence the company's tax strategy.

Gather data on the annual stock-based compensation expenses, sales and marketing, general and administrative, and research and development costs of the company over the years, and analyze the trends, changes, and percentages in these categories. Additionally, compile data on the annual growth rate, risk-free rate of return, market risk premium, beta factor, and cost of debt to understand the key drivers of future growth rates and changes in the beta factor and market risk premium.

Gather data on the corporation's financial performance and tax reconciliation using the UK corporation tax rate, and analyze the trends in revenue, costs, expenses, profits, taxes, and employee costs over the years. Assess the impact of rate differentials in tax jurisdictions and the impact of non-taxable benefits and non-deductible expenses on the reported financial statements.

Gather data on the various types of receivables, including trade receivables, GST receivables, and other receivables, for GasLog Ltd. and its subsidiaries for the years ended December 31, 2017, 2018, and 2019. Gather data on the company's restaurant buildings, the number of company-operated and franchise restaurants, and financial data such as sales, revenues, costs, and earnings. Additionally, assess the company's financial performance over time, including changes in sales, revenues, costs, and earnings, and the differences between company-operated and franchise restaurants.

Gather data on the financial performance of the corporation, including profit for the period and year from continuing operations, profit attributable to owners of the Corporation, and basic earnings per share. Gather data on the company's cash flows from continuing operations activities for the last two fiscal years, including operating, investing, and financing activities. Gather data on the company's investments in various securities and loans, including time deposits, short-term loans, bonds, long-term loans, debt investments, and equity investments. Additionally, assess the composition of the company's investment portfolio, including the percentage constitution of various securities among the total investments. Gather data on the components of net periodic benefit expense for post-retirement benefit plans, including service cost, interest cost, expected return on plan assets, recognition of prior service cost, and other related factors. Gather data on the components of "Other operating income" and "Other operating expenses" in financial statements, and analyze the trends, changes, and impacts of these components over the years. This should include a detailed breakdown of items such as gains from disposal of fixed assets, income from logistics services, rents, services rendered to suppliers, miscellaneous items, expenses from logistics services, losses from disposal of fixed assets, impairment losses on goodwill, research and development expenses, restructuring charges, and amortization of intangibles. Gather financial data for Hilli LLC, including income statements, cash flows, and summarized financial information, and analyze the company's financial performance over time. Additionally, provide insights into the valuation of the oil derivative instrument and the inputs used in its valuation.

Gather data on the revision of prior period financial statements, focusing on the impact of misstatements on financial metrics such as deferred commissions, total current assets, total assets, accrued expenses, total current liabilities, accumulated deficit, and total stockholders’ equity. Gather data on the company's financial assets and liabilities, including contract assets, prepaid expenses, other current assets, deferred revenue, contract liabilities, receivables, financial assets, and financial liabilities, for multiple years. Analyze the trends and changes in these financial components over time, and assess their impact on the company's total assets and equity. Gather data on the financial performance of the company for the fiscal year 2019, including revenue, EBITDA, PBT, profit after tax, EPS, audit fees, tax fees, operating revenue, underlying EBITDA, underlying NPAT, basic EPS, billings, cash EBITDA, adjusted operating profit, and unlevered free cash flow. Gather data on the ownership structure, stock options, ISUs, DSUs, costs, and expenses of Cogeco Communications, a subsidiary of Cogeco, and analyze the trends and changes in these parameters from 2018 to 2019. Additionally, evaluate the expenses, including share-based compensation and other expenses, to provide insights into the financial performance of the company.

Gather data on the net income, basic and diluted earnings per share of the company for fiscal years 2017, 2018, and 2019, and analyze how factors such as weighted average shares outstanding, stock options, and convertible debts contribute to these values. Also, compare these values across the years to identify trends and changes in the net income and earnings per share.

Gather financial data for a company, including income statement data, balance sheet data, and revenue breakdown by domains, hosting and presence, and business applications, for several financial years. Analyze the company's financial performance over time, including trends in revenue, net income, total bookings, and specific revenue streams. Additionally, assess the relationship between different financial metrics and identify any significant changes or patterns in the company's financial performance.

Gather data on the company's billings and financial performance from 2015 to 2019, and analyze how factors such as region, product type, and revenue components contribute to the overall billings and financial health of the company. The data should also support insights into the trends of revenue, cost of revenue, and gross profit over the years.

Gather data on the net debt of a company, including its components such as debt due within one year, long-term debt, preferred shares, total borrowings, loans and other borrowings, and cash and cash equivalents. Gather data on National Storage's acquisitions and financial performance across various regions in Australia and New Zealand, including Brisbane, Gold Coast, Sunshine Coast, Central Coast (NSW), Wollongong, Melbourne, Adelaide, Perth, Auckland (NZ), Hamilton (NZ), Rotorua (NZ), and Tauranga (NZ), for the years 2018 and 2019. Gather data on the company's interest expenses, financing costs, and debt instruments, and analyze the trends in debt structure, financing activities, and cash flow related to debt instruments. Gather data on the net cash provided by operating activities, net cash used in investing activities, and net cash provided by financing activities for multiple entities over several years. Gather data on the movement of stock options, including the number of shares granted, exercised, canceled, expired, forfeited, and outstanding, and analyze how these numbers change over time. Analyze the trends and changes in these financial components, and assess how they contribute to the total prepaid expenses and other assets, as well as the total accrued expenses. Gather data on the company's lease assets and liabilities, including right of use lease assets, total lease assets, current and non-current lease liabilities, and total lease liabilities. Gather data on BCE's financial performance across its Bell Wireless, Bell Wireline, and Bell Media segments for the years 2018 and 2019, and analyze the adjusted EBITDA, operating revenues, operating costs, and balance changes. The analysis should provide insights into the growth, change in percentages, and segment contributions to the overall financial performance of BCE.

Gather data on the hedging reserves, derivative instruments, and gains/losses recorded in other comprehensive income (loss) for the NSPT Group, and analyze how these factors contribute to the Group's financial position. Gather data on taxation trends, including current and deferred tax expenses, tax charges, and tax rates, for a company operating in the UK and overseas. Gather data on the accounts receivable allowances of a company from 2017 to 2019, including balances, provisions, charge-offs, and credit ratings of counterparties. Analyze the company's liquidity over time, including trends in cash and cash equivalents, working capital, and restricted cash, and provide an analysis of how these factors have changed over time. Gather data on purchased intangible assets, including their categories such as core and developed technology, customer-related assets, in-process research and development, and others, and analyze the trends in their values, comparisons between categories, and their impact on the total purchased intangible assets. Gather data on the cash flows of the company, including the different components of cash flows, transactions with related parties, and dividends receivable from associates. Gather data on the net loss per share for a company over multiple years, and analyze the trends in net loss, changes in weighted average shares, and the impact of dilutive securities on the net loss per share. Gather financial data for the company for the years 2017, 2018, and 2019, and analyze the changes in revenue, expenses, profits, and other financial metrics between the years. Gather data on stock-based compensation expenses across different categories, including property, services, SG&A, and research and development, for multiple years. Gather data on the company's intangible assets, revenue, and foreign exchange risks across different regions and currencies, and analyze how changes in foreign exchange rates impact net revenue, total spend, and equity. Gather data on the financial performance of a company in the high-end smartphone and broadband markets, including revenue, operating costs, EBITDA, and free cash flow for the years 2018, 2019, and 2020. Gather data on income taxes, deferred tax assets, and liabilities, including their components and changes over time, and analyze how factors such as tax laws, tax credits, and other temporary differences impact these financial metrics.
